the Quest for a Modern Maltese Paganism -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPagan and Native Faith movements have sprung up across Europe in recent decades, yet little has been published about them compared with their British and American counterparts. Though all such movements valorize human relationships with nature and embrace polytheistic cosmologies, practitioners’ beliefs, practices, goals, and agendas are diverse. Often side by side are groups trying to reconstruct ancient religions motivated by ethnonationalism—especially in post-Soviet societies—and others attracted by imported traditions, such as Wicca, Druidry, Goddess Spirituality, and Core Shamanism. Drawing on ethnographic cases, contributors explore the interplay of neo-nationalistic and neo-colonialist impulses in contemporary Paganism, showing how these impulses play out, intersect, collide, and transform.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aNeopaganismzEurope. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aAmster, Matthew H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aButler, Jenny, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCiancimino Howell, Francesca, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFedele, Anna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGregorius, Fredrik, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGulik, Léon A. van, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHegner, Victoria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKraft, Siv Ellen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPeers, Eleanor, econtributor.4ctb